Class project: UFO Sightings in the United States

1. Introduction

A. Question

My project focuses on UFO sightings in the United States. I am looking at data made public by the Intelligence Authorization Act collected by the Office of Naval Intelligence through the Unidentified Aerial Phenomenon Task Force project. A few questions I have are in regards to the location of these sightings and whether they coincide with the location of military bases. I grew up between a Marine Corps Logistics Base and Fort Irwin so I would spend a lot of time outside with my grandparents watching the sky for shooting stars, the ISS, satellites, and UFOs. I would like to know if it is more common for there to be UFO sightings in areas near military bases or if this just happened to be a random, niche interest of my family. I am planning on running a hypothesis test to know whether there is a statistically significant relationship between UFO sightings and proximity to military bases in the United States.

B. Importance

The reason it is important to look at UFO sightings is because they could possibly be advanced foreign aviation technology. The idea of otherworldly life is exciting, but more than likely, the UFOs we see are just advanced technologies from other countries that we haven't seen before. It is important to track these sightings to find trends in the data that could help strengthen airspace security and answer the public;s questions about UFOs. It is important to note that even if there is some type of correlation between UFO sightings and military bases, there may be other factors to these UFO sightings that I may not have taken into consideration.

C. Data

I got my data from: http://www.uforesearchdb.com/

The website I downloaded the csv file from: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/salmanfaroz/ufo-sightings-in-the-us?resource=download

There are 3437 UFO sightings in the data file. Each sighting includes: Date, Shape, Location, State, Country, and Source.

I am also using another dataset from Kaggle named US Military Bases that contains the geolocation of 776 bases: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/mexwell/us-military-bases

D. Other Analyses

I looked into the data from the database and I see that the database website already put data into categories. For instance, for every UFO shape, there is a histogram with the count of that shape in each state. I think the histograms are a poor way to represent this data so my goal is to use spatial mapping for clearer visualization. I also googled my question regarding whether UFO sightings are more common in areas with military bases and although all articles pointed to a correlation, none of them used any actual data or data mapping to prove this relationship. I also found CNN and VICE articles less than a week old all talking about the rise of UFO sightings and data gathered by the military. This correlation is therefore relevant to today and in need of actual statistical data to either prove or disprove all of these statements in the media.

3. Analyses

Hypothesis Test

$H_0: p = 0.5$

The probability that UFO sightings occur within 10 miles of a military base at random chance is 50%.

$H_A: p > 0.5$

The probability of UFO sightings occurring within 10 miles of a military base is greater than 50%

In[63]:
ufo_sightings_gdf = ufo_sightings_gdf.set_crs("EPSG:4326", allow_override = True)

# created a 10-mile buffer around each military base
military_bases_gdf["buffer"] = military_bases_gdf["geometry"].apply(
    lambda x: x.buffer(16093.4) if x.is_valid else None
)

buffer_gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(geometry = military_bases_gdf["buffer"], crs = military_bases_gdf.crs)

# joined buffer with sightings and removed any possible duplicates
ufo_within_buffer = gpd.sjoin(
    ufo_sightings_gdf, buffer_gdf, how = "inner", predicate = "within"
)

ufo_within_buffer = ufo_within_buffer.drop_duplicates(subset=["geometry"])

ufo_within_count = len(ufo_within_buffer)
total_ufo_count = len(ufo_sightings_gdf)
proportion_within = ufo_within_count / total_ufo_count

print("UFO sightings within 10 miles of military bases:", ufo_within_count)
print("Total UFO sightings:", total_ufo_count)
print("Proportion of sightings within 10 miles:", proportion_within)

In[22]:
def generate_proportion(n, heads_probability):
    rand_nums = np.random.rand(n)
    num_heads = np.sum(rand_nums <= heads_probability)
    return num_heads / n

generate_proportion(3396, 0.5)

example_proportion = generate_proportion(3396, 0.5)
example_proportion

In[81]:
null_dist = []

for i in range(10000):

    simulated_null_stat = generate_proportion(3396, 0.5)
    null_dist.append(simulated_null_stat)

plt.hist(null_dist, edgecolor = "black", bins = 50); 

plt.title("Simulated Null Distribution for Hypothesis Test")
plt.xlabel("Simulated Proportions")
plt.ylabel("Frequency")

plt.plot(proportion_within, 30, '.', markersize = 30, color = "red");

plt.text(0.6, 60, "Actual Proportion of Population", fontsize = 10, color = "red");
In[80]:
p_value = np.mean(np.array(null_dist) >= proportion_within)

p_value

print("p-value:", p_value)

p-value: 0.0

Since the p-value (0.0) is less than alpha (0.05) I reject the null hypothesis. The probability of seeing UFOs near military bases is not just due to random chance.

In order to use this type of analysis you must be looking at the full population of UFO sightings. I have decided that this data is representative of all of the sightings that the government has for the US because all I removed were points without any actual locations attached as well as data from other countries, but other than that I used all the thousands of points. If I would have just picked maybe 300 data points at random, then I would have used a different type of hypothesis test.

4. Conclusions

After comparing my data sets it is fair to say that I have found a clear link between UFO sightings and the distance someone is to a military base. I found this very insightful because I grew up with a father in the Marine Corps and have only lived in areas near military bases so I just assumed that seeing UFOs was a common thing for people. This project has given me a wider view on how simply living near military bases can affect someone's understanding of what is normal. This makes me even more curious to explore the effects of living near military bases on peoples' lives. I found a 2013 article from The National Library of Medicine titled "Exploring the Association Between Military Base Neighborhood Characteristics and Soldiers' and Airmen's Outcomes". This article only talks about the airmen themselves though so I think it would be really fun to explore this topic further.

Regarding future directions I can take with my data, I would really like to create an interactive map of the United States where you can click on each state and not only view the military bases, but the branch of each base. It would be a lot easier to see the correlations and it might clarify a thing or two about what branches are more involved with aviation (obviously airforce but I would like to know if there is a close second or if this data disproves my assumption). I would also like to map out the bases with their area, not just a point. I have the proper data to do that but I couldn't figure out how to so I just chose not to include that in my project.

I would love to conclude this paper by saying that UFO sightings are just new military technology that we don't know about yet but that is obviously not the case. My data shows that UFO sightings are way more common near military bases but there is no concluding factor of what causes this. I could also say that UFOs are extraterrestrial and that their landing pads just happen to be at military bases where they can conduct universal diplomacy easier, but my data doesn't prove that either. All I can say for sure is that there is a strong correlation between UFOs and their distance spotted within 10 miles of a military base. In the future, I hope to be able to answer all of my burning questions, but for now I am glad to have gained a bit of insight through YDATA 123.

Reviwer email address: josie.russell@yale.edu

Summary

This project sought to investigate whether there tends to be more UFO sightings near military bases than away from them. There is a pause to investigate and view shapes of UFO sightings, and then a few maps of the US depicting the locations of UFO sightings and military bases, both by state and in general. These latter maps show that there is a possibility of more UFO sightings being near military bases, so a hypothesis test is used to determine if these sightings likely occur by chance or not. The null hypothesis is then rejected, suggesting that there is a relationship between UFO sightings and military bases that is not only left to chance.

1. Overall strengths and weaknesses

I think that overall, this is a really strong project period. Your graphs are beautiful and relatively easy to read, and they lend themselves to explaining why you proceeded to run a hypothesis test. For the most part, there was also a consistent line of logic in your project that (satisfyingly) led to a rejection of your null hypothesis. I think that I learned a lot here!

Some things that I would suggest are just to make the transitions between steps more fluid, and explain what you're doing initially so that the reader doesn't have to guess. Additionally, the UFO shape section seems a little out of place, and the project goes over the 10 page limit (which is an easy fix). Still, this project was intruiging and well-executed.

2. Major revisions

  • Not HUGE but something: your visualizations come a little abruptly sometimes. Especially with the third figure under the Geopandas section, I think including a subtitle or a line of writing just explaining what you're visualizing before hand will help orient the reader.
  • In your appendix, I think that it would be helpful to label each of the graphs included or tell where they came from in your code above so that it's easier to place them within your project.
  • The biggest issue here is just that your conclusion and reflection trickle onto page 12; I think that almost all of what you note is really interesting, though, so I would suggest moving more of your code from above to the appendix in order to meet the page limit.
  • For the UFO Sightings by Shape chart, I think I'm a little confused as to why it was included. Maybe include a few sentences about why shapes of UFOs is important to view when considering your larger question of sightings and military bases.

3. Minor revisions

  • For the UFO sightings by shape bubble chart, maybe try altering the color palette used for each category. This isn't a large problem at all, but without looking very carefully and zooming in, some of the colors make it easy for the bubble of one shape to get lost in the color of another, larger one.
  • Maybe in the "Combining Data through Geopandas" section insert a few brief comments between the code just to help orient the reader to what you're doing.
  • Maybe also just do a quick read-through for spelling errors (not having autocorrect was hard for me too).
  • In your figure for Military Bases and UFO sightings, maybe change the colors to colors more color-map diagonal, like red and green. Not huge, but the green and blue are a little challenging to tell apart (but pretty!)
    • Also for this figure: below in your description be a little more specific about $why$ you can't rule out the correlation.
  • Perhaps explain a little specifically about why you chose to run a hypothesis test on probability. I think the transitions are just a little jarring for the reader.
  • Maybe explicity identify what parts of the hypothesis test are what: for example, above the code you use to create your observed statistic, just write a line saying that's what you're about to do.
  • In the graph of your null distribution, perhaps include axis labels just for specificity.
  • After you determine your p-value you write a second paragraph justifying why a hypothesis test is accurate; I think this might work better if placed before your hypothesis test.

Summary

This project aimed to explore whether there is a correlation between UFO sightings and proximity to United States military bases, which could provide insight into what people are really seeing when they claim to sight a UFO. The project creates visualizations of data - such as the shapes of UFO sightings, and others in the appendix - which may not be totally connected to the research questions but are still interesting to see, as well as the locations of military bases and UFO sightings on a map of the United States. Then, a hypothesis test of proportions is done on the probability that a UFO sighting occurs within 10 miles of a military base; the test uses a null hypothesis of random chance 50% of this occuring and an alternative hypothesis of greater than 50% chance. The conclusion is a strong correlation (with a p-value of 0.0), but no proof of causation.

1. Overall strengths and weaknesses

I thought that your topic was very interesting and that your results could be used to understand why certain areas in the US have far greater UFO sightings than others, and what these UFOs actually are. Your visualizations were well-made and mostly had a clear aim in answering your research question, but I felt that your visualization of the UFO shapes could have been used more, possibly through some sort of K-Nearest Neighbors algorithm for considering UFO shape (or the time of the year data). However, this isn't necessary for your project's goal and could take up too much space - I just think it would be an interesting analysis. The hypothesis test was convincing, and though I appreciate your defence for using a hypothesis test, I didn't think that it was necessary; in other words, I was convinced there was a correlation even without your defence.

3. Minor revisions

Summary

This project uses United States UFO sighting data to see where UFO sightings commonly occur and looks at other trends in the data. First, it looks at what shapes/types of UFOs are most commonly reported. It then compares what states have the most active military bases and where the most UFO sightings are reported, then plots where UFO sightings were recorded and where military bases are. It conducts an analysis to see if there is a correlation between short distance from a military base and frequent UFO sightings, finding that the number of UFOs seen near a military base is not random chance.

1. Overall Strengths and Weaknesses

I really thought that the combination of graphs, maps, and the hypothesis test done was well-balanced!
